% test_screen_render_direct.trx -- D5 from review_screen_system.md.
% Exercises screen-render's direct-::write-to-STDOUT path that
% screen-render-to (and therefore test_screen_render.trx) cannot
% reach: m_stdout flush-first (A5), the 4 KiB stack buffer + chunked
% drain, the EINTR/EAGAIN poll-and-retry loop, and the > 4 KiB
% single-chunk fallback.
%
% The render emit code itself (cursor moves, SGR diff, UTF-8 encode)
% is byte-asserted by test_screen_render.trx via screen-render-to.
% This complement only verifies the I/O wrapper.
%
% Run model: screen-render writes ANSI bytes to STDOUT_FILENO.  Under
% run_all.sh stdout is captured by the runner; the rendered bytes
% mingle with this test's = output but the sentinel check
% (`^__test_ok__$`) still finds the trailing line because = writes a
% newline and the rendered output doesn't end on the sentinel string.

/passed 0 def
/failed 0 def
% restore-immune failure counter (string byte writes are unjournaled
% and local-VM, invisible to heap probes): the file THROWS at EOF so
% failed assertions gate the suite verdict.
/rt-fails 1 string def
rt-fails 0 16#0#b put
/total  0 def
/rt-ok {
    /total total 1 add def
    exch
    { pop /passed passed 1 add def }
    { /failed failed 1 add def
      rt-fails 0  rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 1 add dup 255 gt { pop 255 } if /byte-type cast  put
      (FAILED: ) print = } if-else
} def

% --- 1. Smallest possible render ------------------------------------------
% 1x1 screen, single 'A'.  Tests the m_stdout-flush-first path on a
% trivial diff (~25 bytes total output).
1 1 make-screen /s1 exch def
s1 0 0 65 7 0 0 screen-put-cell pop
s1 screen-render
s1 screen? (smallest render returned same screen) rt-ok

% Re-render unchanged screen produces zero bytes -- still must succeed.
s1 screen-render
s1 screen? (no-op render returned same screen) rt-ok

% --- 2. Buffer-drain path (output > 4 KiB) --------------------------------
% A 40x12 fresh screen first-render emits roughly:
%   for each cell: cursor-position CSI (~6 bytes) + SGR (~18 bytes) +
%   character (1 byte) -- but adjacent cells with same SGR skip the
%   SGR, so realistic ~10-15 bytes/cell.  40*12 = 480 cells -> ~6 KiB.
% This forces screen-render's flush_sink to drain the 4 KiB stack
% buffer at least twice during a single render call.
40 12 make-screen /s2 exch def
% Vary fg per column so SGR re-emits roughly every cell -- inflates
% per-cell bytes and pushes the total well past 4 KiB.
0 1 11 {|r|#3
    0 1 39 {|c|#2
        s2 c r 65 c add 26 mod 65 add 1 c 16 mod add 0 0 screen-put-cell pop
    } for
} for
s2 screen-render
s2 screen-cols 40 eq (4-KiB+ render returned screen) rt-ok

% --- 3. Mixed-with-print interleaving (A5 footgun documented) -------------
% screen-render flushes m_stdout before its direct ::write, so prior
% print bytes still in m_stdout's buffer reach the terminal BEFORE
% the render bytes.  Verify the call sequence doesn't crash; byte-
% order checking proper requires byte-level capture which only
% screen-render-to supports (and is covered there in test_screen_render.trx).
1 1 make-screen /s3 exch def
s3 0 0 88 7 0 0 screen-put-cell pop
(\nMIXED-BEFORE) print
s3 screen-render
(MIXED-AFTER\n) print
s3 screen? (mix-with-print returned screen) rt-ok

(\npassed: ) print passed = (failed: ) print failed = (total: ) print total =
failed 0 eq { (test_screen_render_direct OK) } { (test_screen_render_direct FAILED) } if-else =
rt-fails 0 get /integer-type cast 0 gt { /rt-assertions-failed throw } if
(__test_ok__) =
